net.sf.mmm.util.collection.api

Interface GenericTreeNode<CHILD extends Node<PARENT>,PARENT extends GenericTreeNode<CHILD,PARENT>>

  • Type Parameters:
    CHILD - is the generic type of the children.
    PARENT - is the generic type of the parent.
    All Superinterfaces:
    Node<PARENT>
    All Known Subinterfaces:
    TreeNode<NODE>
    All Known Implementing Classes:
    AbstractGenericTreeNode, AbstractTreeNode, TreeNodeSimple

    public interface GenericTreeNode<CHILD extends Node<PARENT>,PARENT extends GenericTreeNode<CHILD,PARENT>>
extends Node<PARENT>
    This is the interface for the node of a tree. The tree itself is defined by the root-node which is its only node in the tree that has no parent.
    A GenericTreeNode is generic and allows different types for <CHILD> and <PARENT> (e.g. to implement a folder that can only have a folder as parent but can have any resource as child that is of type folder or file). For a regular simple tree node you can use TreeNode.
    Since:
    3.0.0
    Author:
    Joerg Hohwiller (hohwille at users.sourceforge.net)

      • getChildren

        List<? extends CHILD> getChildren()
        This method gets the List containing all children of this GenericTreeNode. The List may be empty - in such case we call this GenericTreeNode a leaf . Each item of the returned List is called a child or child-node. It should return this GenericTreeNode as parent.
        Returns:
        the List containing all children of this GenericTreeNode.

      • isDescendant

        boolean isDescendant(CHILD node)
        This method determines if this GenericTreeNode is a descendant of the given node. In other words this method checks if this GenericTreeNode is the direct or indirect child of the given node.
        Parameters:
        node - is the GenericTreeNode to check (the potential ancestor).
        Returns:
        true if this GenericTreeNode is an descendant of the given node .
